I have some Actors inside a Table and when i want to remove i used to call Actor.remove(). 

In previous version of libgdx this will call the method in Table class.

``` java
public boolean removeActor (Actor actor) {
        if (!super.removeActor(actor)) return false;
        Cell cell = getCell(actor);
        if (cell != null) cell.actor = null;
        return true;
    }
```

But in the current version of Libgdx it will call the method in Group class

``` java
    public boolean removeActor (Actor actor, boolean unfocus) {
        if (!children.removeValue(actor, true)) return false;
        if (unfocus) {
            Stage stage = getStage();
            if (stage != null) stage.unfocus(actor);
        }
        actor.setParent(null);
        actor.setStage(null);
        childrenChanged();
        return true;
    }
```

The problem is because the Actor class directy calls removeActor(this,true) and this method doesnt exist in table class. And this makes the cell never  going null.  

``` java
public boolean remove () {
        if (parent != null) return parent.removeActor(this, true);
        return false;
    }
```

Using 1.5.6-SNAPSHOT, it's possible to get text to wrap in such a way that the last row extends outside the computed bounds.  See screenshot and code below.

This issue seems to be quite sensitive to the specific text and font scale, so I'm guessing it's some sort of edge case in the text wrapping code.

![fontsizeissue](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1848870/6930212/ee85fc88-d84c-11e4-9ac6-c16d226f70e0.png)

```
public class FontSizeIssue extends ApplicationAdapter {

    private static final int GAME_HEIGHT = 120;

    private Stage stage;
    private float gameScale;

    @Override
    public void create () {
        gameScale = (float) GAME_HEIGHT / Gdx.graphics.getHeight();
        int gameWidth = (int) (Gdx.graphics.getWidth() * gameScale + 0.5);
        stage = new Stage(new FitViewport(gameWidth, GAME_HEIGHT));
        Gdx.input.setInputProcessor(stage);
        resize(Gdx.graphics.getWidth(), Gdx.graphics.getHeight());
        FreeTypeFontGenerator generator = new FreeTypeFontGenerator(Gdx.files.internal("tubular.ttf"));
        FreeTypeFontGenerator.FreeTypeFontParameter parameter = new FreeTypeFontGenerator.FreeTypeFontParameter();
        parameter.size = (int) (5 / gameScale + 0.5);
        BitmapFont font = generator.generateFont(parameter);
        font.getData().setScale(gameScale);
        Label.LabelStyle labelStyle = new Label.LabelStyle();
        labelStyle.font = font;
        labelStyle.fontColor = Color.WHITE;
        String text = "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, sea cu labore incorrupte persequeris, ne quodsi dolorum percipit pri. Ne tempor intellegam sed. Ne qui noluisse delectus. Mei ut officiis antiopam.";
        Table table = new Table();
        table.setFillParent(true);
        table.debug();
        stage.addActor(table);
        addLabel(table, text, labelStyle);
        addLabel(table, text, labelStyle);
        addLabel(table, text, labelStyle);
        addLabel(table, text, labelStyle);
        addLabel(table, text, labelStyle);
        addLabel(table, text, labelStyle);
    }

    private void addLabel(Table table, String text, Label.LabelStyle labelStyle) {
        Label label = new Label(text, labelStyle);
        label.setWrap(true);
        table.add(label).fillX().expandX().row();
    }

    @Override
    public void render () {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(0, 0, 0, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
        stage.act(Gdx.graphics.getDeltaTime());
        stage.draw();
    }
}
```

Regarding BatchTileMapRenderer, when the Batch is passed onto the constructor, thus the renderer not owning the batch, it should not call the batch.begin() and batch.end() on beginRender() and endRender() methods (should it?). I've created a subclass that overrides both methods to change this and its compatible with other batch drawing. 

@Override
    protected void beginRender() {
        if (ownsBatch) {
            super.beginRender();
        }
    }

```
@Override
protected void endRender() {
    if (ownsBatch) {
        super.endRender();
    }
}
```

